<target_code>
Here is the code of OS_NotifyEvent:
```c
int32 OS_NotifyEvent(OS_Event_t event, osal_id_t object_id, void *data)
{
    int32 status;

    if (OS_SharedGlobalVars.EventHandler != NULL)
    {
        status = OS_SharedGlobalVars.EventHandler(event, object_id, data);
    }
    else
    {
        status = OS_SUCCESS;
    }

    return status;
}
```

Please find suspicious code fragments in the code and report them. Other agents can not investigate other fragments that you do not report, so it is very important to find all suspicious fragments without missing any. Report the suspicious fragments AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.
explanation: No calls to memcmp (or any other C standard library string-comparison functions) appear in this function. The code only checks a function-pointer against NULL and calls it, returning an int32 status. There are no operations on null-terminated strings (no char* manipulations, no strcmp/strncmp/memcmp usage) in the provided fragment, so there are no places here that could violate MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.14. (Any use of memcmp inside the referenced EventHandler is outside the scope of this fragment and would need to be inspected where that function is defined.)
